solutions.content:
After my first few tries end up TLE, I find this approach that takes ```O(nums.length)``` time. As ```1<=nums.length<=10^5``` and ```1<=k,nums[i]<=10^9```, this approach should be faster than ```O(k)``` and ```O(nums[i])``` approaches and past all test cases.
My idea is that the maximum possible integer to append is ```maxnum = k+nums.length```, then we can take the integers from ```1``` to ```maxnum``` as our first guess. Of course we would have more integers than needed at this time, but we have to delete some integers according to the rule. We traverse ```nums``` to delete integers from our guess, then we delete integers from big to small until only ```k``` integers left.
```
#include <unordered_set>
class Solution {
public:
    long long minimalKSum(vector<int>& nums, int k){
        unordered_set<int> freq;
        long long maxnum = k+nums.size(); // maximum possible integer to be appended
        long long sum = (1+maxnum)*maxnum/2; // calculate the sum and subtract from it later
        int count = maxnum; // currently we have count integers, which is more than we need
        for(auto num: nums){
            if(freq.find(num)==freq.end()){
                freq.insert(num);
                if(num<=maxnum){ // need to delete num from our candidate integers
                    sum -= num;
                    count --;
                }
            }
        }
		// delete integers from big to small until only k integers left
        // goes into while loop at most nums.length time, when all nums[i]>maxnum
        int i = maxnum;
        while(
            if(freq.find(i)==freq.end()){
                sum -= i;
                count --;
            }
            i --;
        }
        return sum;
    }
};
```
We traverse ```nums``` for one time, and goes into the while loop no more than ```nums.length``` time.  No sorting is needed, the time complexity should be ```O(nums.length)```. Also the space complexicy is ```O(nums.length)``` since we keeps a set of nums for quick query.

