solutions.content:
APPROACH

formula to be used
**Sum of first n natural numbers:**
**n*(n+1)/2**

Initially we compute the sum of first k natural numbers using the formula
**Sum = k*(k+1)/2;**
Now we will adjust the sum according to the values present in the array

*we sort the original array and then traverse from left to right*

whenever we find a value which is less than k,,
we deduct that value from total  and 
add k+1 to total sum(updating k to k+1)

there is a edge case,,
that if nums[i] contains duplicate values,
then we will update sum for only 1 value

**Example:**

nums = [4,5,6,6,8], k=10

-- sum of first k(10) numbers is n(n+1)/2=55
now if **(nums[i]<=k)** we update the sum

---**sum=55,k=10**
for i=0,
nums[i]=4 ,4<=10
sum=sum-nums[i]=55-4=51
k=k+1=11
sum=sum+k=51+11=62

**sum=62,k=11**
for i=1,
nums[i] = 5, 5<=11
sum=62-5=57
k++=12
sum+=k = 57+12=69

**sum=69, k=12**
for i=2,
nums[i]=6, 6<=12
sum=69-6=63
k++=13
sum+=k=63+13=76

**sum=76, k=13**
for i=3,
nums[i]=nums[i-1]=6
i++; continue;

**sum=76, k=13**
for i=4,
nums[i]=8, 8<=13
sum = 76-8=68
k++=14;
sum+=k = 68+14=82

**O/P
sum=82**


**My Approach:**  **Time Complexity - O(n)**

```
class Solution {
public:
    long long minimalKSum(vector<int>& nums, int k) {

        long long int ans=k;
        long long int x=k;                                                                             
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());

        ans = (x*(x+1))/2;  //sum of first k variables
        int i=0;  //pointer to traverse array
        while(i<nums.size() && k>=nums[i])  //checking if we dont go out of bounds and whether we need to update our sum
        {
            if(i>0 && nums[i]==nums[i-1])  //for duplicate elements
            {
                i++;continue;
            }
			k++;
            ans=ans-nums[i]+k;   //updating the sum
            i++;
        }
        return ans;
    }
};
```

