# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
If you are standing on an element then you should have taken all the elements that comes before that into your sum.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
- first of all sort the array.
- Then initialise `sum` to 0 and `prev` to 0.
- Run a for loop from 0 to size of array .
- if(k>= nums[i]-prev-1), which means that all numbers between nums[i] and prev are to be taken into sum.
- if (k<nums[i]-prev-1),  then k will exhaust within nums[i] and nums[i+1].
- if we don't find all the k numbers within the given array, we have to find them outside of it.
- At last return sum.$$$$$$$$$$O(n)$$$$$$$$$$

# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(nlogn) + O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
#define ll long long 
class Solution {
public:
    long long minimalKSum(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        ll n = nums.size();
        sort(nums.begin(),nums.end());
        ll sum=0;
        ll prev=0;
        for(ll i=0 ; i<n ; i++)
        {
            ll a = nums[i];
            if(prev==a) continue;
            if(a-prev-1 <= k)
            {
                sum += (a*(a-1))/2;
                sum-= (prev*(prev+1))/2;
                k-=a-prev-1;

            }
            else 
            {
                sum += ((prev+k) * (prev+k+1))/2;
                sum-= (prev*(prev+1))/2;
                k=0;
                break;
            }
            if(k==0) break;

            prev = nums[i];            
        }

        if(k!=0)
        {
            sum += ((prev+k) * (prev+k+1))/2;
            sum-= (prev*(prev+1))/2;
            k=0;
        }

        return sum;
    }
};
```

