# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
We can definitely say that the k numbers we need will be amongst (n+k)
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
To find the required sum of the first unique k numbers, we first find sum of first (n+k) numbers.
Then now we need to subtract the (n) numbers which does exist in our given nums.

so to find these numbers we first Subtract the numbers which are common in both n+k elements and nums.

Used unordered_set so that same number does not subtract again.

now we remove leftover numbers from (n+k) numbers from backside.    
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    long long minimalKSum(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int n=nums.size();

        long long ans = 1ll*(n+k)*(n+k+1)/2;
        // now have to remove n elements

        int cnt=0;
        unordered_set<int> s;

        for(int p=0;p<n;p++)
        {
            if(s.find(nums[p])==s.end() && nums[p] <= n+k)
            {
                ans = ans-nums[p];
                cnt++;
                s.insert(nums[p]);
            }
        }

        int j=n+k;

        while(cnt<n)
        {
            if(s.find(j)==s.end())
            {
                cnt++;
                ans = ans-j;
            }

            j--;
        }

        return ans;
    }
};
```

