# Idea
- Working with arrays is troublesome since they are ordered so instead we convert them to sets.
- In particular, ordered sets would require higher time complexity so we use unordered sets which accomplish the same task but faster.
- Using sets also solves any issues with duplicate integers within an array. 
- We will iterate through `set1` to check whether `set2` contains any common elements. 
- Every common element we find will go into `set3`.
- We do not directly remove from `set1` and`set2` because this messes up the for loop iterations. 
- Finally, we iterate through `set3` which is all the common elements and we remove them from both `set1` and `set2`. 
- Now, `set1` and `set2` are left with only **distinct** elements.

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<vector<int>> findDifference(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {
        // Initialize a set for each array and a common set
        unordered_set<int> set1(nums1.begin(), nums1.end());
        unordered_set<int> set2(nums2.begin(), nums2.end());
        unordered_set<int> set3;

        // Find common values of each set
        for (auto p : set1){
            if (set2.find(p) != set2.end()){
                set3.insert(p);
            }
        }

        // Remove common elements from both sets
        for (auto p : set3){
            set1.erase(p), set2.erase(p);
        }

        // Translate sets into array answer
        vector<vector<int>> res;
        res.push_back(vector<int>(set1.begin(), set1.end()));
        res.push_back(vector<int>(set2.begin(), set2.end()));
        return res;
    }
};
```
