# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. --->
Consider the set theory.
Let $S_1$ denote the set consisting of all distinct elements in nums1.
Let $S_2$ denote the set consisting of all distinct elements in nums2.

Then the union of $ S_1 \cup S_2$ can be decomposed into the disjoint union of sets  as follows
$$ S_1 \cup S_2=(S_1\setminus S_2)\cup (S_1\cap S_2)\cup (S_2\setminus S_1)$$

The answer is in fact $$[S_1\setminus S_2, S_2\setminus S_1]$$ in the proper data structure.

C++ STL unordered_set is exactly the implementation for set in the math sense.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    vector<int> set_diff(vector<int>& n1, vector<int>& n2){
        unordered_set<int> S1_minus_S2;
        unordered_set<int> S2;
        for(int x: n2)
            if (S2.find(x)==S2.end()) S2.insert(x);
        for(int y: n1)
            if (S2.find(y)==S2.end()) S1_minus_S2.insert(y);
        return vector<int> (S1_minus_S2.begin(), S1_minus_S2.end());
    }
    vector<vector<int>> findDifference(vector<int>& nums1, vector<int>& nums2) {
        return {set_diff(nums1, nums2), set_diff(nums2, nums1)};
    }
};
```
